did.abstract: Mary Daly (1928-2010) was a radical feminist theologian, author, lecturer, and professor of religious and women's studies. This collection includes records of her personal and professional life. Of particular interest are Daly's fight with Boston College, her writing process, and her argument with Audre Lorde.
did.langmaterial: Materials are primarily in English. There are some works by Daly in translation, research materials, and Graduate Studies records from Fribourg University in other languages, including German, French, Dutch, Korean, Mandarin, Latin, and Greek.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for use without restriction beyond the standard terms and conditions of Smith College Special Collections.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Mary Daly started donating her papers to the Sophia Smith Collection in 2009. This collection is comprised of six separate accessions received from Daly and her estate in 2009-2010, and one received in 2012.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The collection is arranged into four series: Professional materials, Writings, Correspondence, and Personal records. Series are arranged roughly in the order they arrived at the archive. Oversize, AV, digital, ephemera, and books appear at the end of each series.

bioghist.head: Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Mary Daly, a radical feminist theologian who referred to herself as a Positively Revolting Hag, was born in Schnectady, New York, in 1928, the only child of a homemaker mother and a traveling salesman father. She was raised Catholic and attended Catholic schools. Early in her childhood, Daly had mystical experiences in which she felt the presence of divinity in nature.

She received a BA in English from the College of St. Rose in Albany, NY in 1950; an MA from Catholic University of America in 1952; and a Ph.D. in Religion from the School of Sacred Theology, St. Mary's, Notre Dame, in 1954. Unable to find a school in America that would allow a woman to obtain a"canonical" Doctorate in Sacred Theology, she went to Fribourg, Switzerland, where the education was state-controlled and could not legally exclude women. There she received a Doctorate in Theology and a Ph.D. in Philosophy as well as a Licentiate in Sacred Theology.

When she returned to the United States in 1966, she took a tenure track position at Boston College. Her first book, The Church and the Second Sex (1968) was influenced by a visit to Rome during Vatican II. The book, called a "searing expose of Christian misogyny, especially in the Catholic Church," critiqued the patriarchal structure of the Catholic Church and its detrimental effect on shaping women's lives and self-image. The book established Daly as a radical feminist theologian and a powerful voice of dissension, and Boston College fired her soon after its publication. However, amidst student protests and public outcry, Daly was reinstated and given tenure.

She went on to teach at Boston College for thirty-three years and published seven more books: Gyn/Ecology: The Metaethics of Radical Feminism (1978), Pure Lust: Elemental Feminist Philosophy (1984), Beyond God the Father (1985), Webster's First New Intergaliactic Wickedary of the English Language (with Jane Caputi; 1987), Outercourse (1992), Quintessence (1998), and Amazon Grace (2006).

Daly regularly toured nationally and internationally, lecturing, speaking and teaching at over three hundred college and universities. In addition to her own work, Daly was connected to many other feminist scholars, theologians and radicals of her day including Adrienne Rich, Diana Davies, Andrea Dworkin, Artemis March, Sonia Johnson, Jane Caputi, Merlin Stone, Janice Raymond, Robin Morgan, Julia Penelope, Gloria Steinem, Roseanne Barr, Pauli Murray, Linda Barufaldi, and Emily Culpepper. Daly retired from Boston College in 1999, although she claimed she was forced to do so. She died in Gardner, Massachusetts in January 2010.

phystech.head: Physical Characteristics and Technical Requirements
phystech.p: This collection contains materials received from the donor in digital form that are not currently available online. Please consult with Special Collections staff to request access to this digital content. The collection also contains several AV formats, including audio cassettes, VHS tapes, and CDs.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Mary Daly papers, Sophia Smith Collection, SSC-MS-00637, Smith College Special Collection, Northampton, Massachusetts.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: The collection came to the Smith Special Collections in seven instalments, starting when Daly was alive and continuing after her death with a few boxes of personal materials and materials related to her death. The collection was in considerable disorder when it came to us, with all types of materials mixed together, much without any labels.

In 2019, a team of processors began to reorganize the collection. The team was made up of Madison White, Scott Biddle, Sylvia Hickman, and two student workers, Sky Karp and Isabel Montesanto. First we removed all student grades and assessments. We put all unfoldered materials into folders and rewrote illegible labels. While refoldering and weeding the collection, we noticed groupings of 5-20 folders on correspondence, writings, Boston College materials, and personal records, which implied that these had once been series within the collection. We therefore decided to seperate the collection into these four series, keeping each series in roughly the order that it arrived to us. Once we seperated materials into series, we did not arrange materials any further.
The contents of 4 floppy disks in this collection has been copied to networked storage for preservation and access. 3 disks were blank so they were discarded.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection consists of the personal and professional papers of Mary Daly. It includes correspondence, including fan mail; drafts and galleys of many of Daly's books; financial information; research files and subject files (on topics including students, colleagues and public figures); documents pertaining to legal disputes with Boston College in 1969 and 1999; personal files re: health, pets, automotive, investments, medical, etc.; books; and teaching materials, including course outlines, syllabi, and confidential student records. Of particular interest are Daly's fight with Boston College, her writing process, and her argument with Audre Lorde.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: In 2019, student grades and evaluations were removed from the collection and destroyed. Duplicate materials were removed, and books not written by Daly were weeded out. A full list of the books in Daly's library can be found in Series IV. AV materials - duplicates and audio/video cassettes not pertaining to Daly were also removed. For a full list of these, please see Special Collections staff.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: To the extent that she owns copyright, Mary Daly has assigned the copyright in her works to Smith College; however, copyright in other items in this collection may be held by their respective creators. For reproductions of materials that are governed by fair use as defined under U. S. Copyright Law, no permission to cite or publish is required. For instances which may regard materials in the collection not created by Daly, researchers are responsible for determining who may hold materials' copyrights and obtaining approval from them. Researchers do not need anything further from Smith College Special Collections to move forward with their use.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains the professional records of Daly. Included in this series are course materials spanning much of Daly's career at Boston College, including syllabi and class notes, course evaluations and correspondence with current and former students, including Janice Raymond, later author of the controversial The Transsexual Empire. This series also includes legal documents, letters of support, clippings from the press, and fundraising documents related to Daly's "harassment" by Boston College and the Center for Individual Rights regarding her application for tenure and her refusal to teach male and female students together. Researchers can also find flyers, schedules and some correspondence related to Daly's speaking engagements and conferences. More correspondence about Boston College disputes and speaking engagements can be found in the correspondence series. Records related to Daly's writing career and book tours can be found in writings.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains Daly's records pertaining to her journal articles and books. Materials include manuscripts and drafts, research files, correspondence with publishers, royalty information, and book tour speeches. More correspondence with publishers and all fan mail is located in the correspondence series. Further research files can be found in the personal and correspondence series.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains both personal and professional correspondence to and from Mary Daly, as well as fan mail. Correspondence is with students, colleagues, lawyers, publishers, and friends. Files also contain non-correspondence materials by and about people, including writings, theses, articles, and newspaper clippings. Some files contain no correspondence, just materials relating to the person listed- a name listed is not a guarantee Daly maintained correspondence with that person. There are also organizational and academic newsletters and ephemera as well as subject files interspersed in the series.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains personal records of Daly, including financial reports, insurance, vet and house bills, school and university papers, family and genealogy research, photographs, and miscellaneous newspaper clippings. Personal correspondence to friends and family can be found in the correspondence series. More newspaper clippings can be found in the writings and correspondence series.
